'''Alexander Noah Paulsen'''  (born 4 July 2002) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[I liga]] club [[Lechia Gdańsk]], on loan from [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

Born in Auckland, Paulsen joined the academy of [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] in 2018 and signed his first professional contract in September 2021.<ref name=":2" /> After establishing himself as the club’s first-choice goalkeeper, he signed for Bournemouth in June 2024.<ref name="auto1">{{cite news|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2024/June/4/cherries-complete-signing-of-goalkeeper-paulsen|website=[[AFC Bournemouth]]|date=4 June 2024|access-date=10 February 2025|title=Cherries complete signing of goalkeeper Paulsen}}</ref> He was subsequently loaned to sister club [[Auckland FC]] for their inaugural [[A-League Men]] season,<ref name=":1" /> before joining Lechia Gdańsk on loan for the 2025–26 campaign.<ref name=":3" /> Paulsen represented [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand]] at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020]] and [[Football at the 2024 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2024]] Olympics.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12356355/football-at-olympics-tokyo-2020-which-premier-league-stars-are-heading-to-the-games | title=Football at Olympics Tokyo 2020: Which Premier League stars are heading to the Games? | publisher=SkySports | date=15 July 2021 | accessdate=17 July 2021 | author=Ben Grounds}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/117115849/fifa-under17-world-cup-new-zealand-stay-alive-thanks-to-alex-paulsens-saves | title=Fifa Under-17 World Cup: New Zealand stay alive thanks to Alex Paulsen's saves | publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] | date=2 November 2019 | accessdate=18 July 2021 | author=Andrew Voerman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/143021?newsfeedId=1275622|website=[[New Zealand Football]]|date=10 July 2024|access-date=12 August 2024|title=Men's Football Team Announced for Paris 2024}}</ref>

==Early life==
Paulsen was born in [[Auckland]] to a South African father and Namibian mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/who-is-alex-paulsen-wellington-phoenix-a-league/|title=Meet the 21yo goalkeeper taking the A-Leagues by storm: 'There will be clubs after him'|date=28 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/u17worldcup/brazil2019/news/paulsen-bounces-back-new-zealand-canada-u17wc | title=Paulsen Bounces Back at First Opportunity | publisher=FIFA | date=2 November 2019 | accessdate=18 July 2021}}</ref> He played [[futsal]] throughout his childhood, and only committed to playing football as a goalkeeper at the age of 13 after beginning as an outfielder.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/match-programme-feature-alex-paulsen/|title=Match Programme Feature - Alex Paulsen|date=4 December 2023}}</ref> Paulsen initially played in the youth ranks of [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] and then [[Onehunga Sports]] under the tutelage of noted youth development coach [[Hiroshi Miyazawa (footballer)|Hiroshi Miyazawa]]. In 2018, aged 15, Paulsen moved to Wellington to join the [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] academy through their affiliation with Onehunga Sports, following in the footsteps of fellow graduates [[Sarpreet Singh]] and [[Max Mata]].<ref name="auto"/>

==Club career==
===Wellington Phoenix===
====Early career====
After progressing through the Wellington Phoenix age-grade sides, Paulsen was regularly named as a substitute for [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Reserves]] throughout the [[2018–19 New Zealand Football Championship|2018–19]] and [[2019–20 New Zealand Football Championship|2019–20]] [[New Zealand Football Championship]] seasons, but did not make an appearance. During this time, Paulsen played for Wellington Phoenix affiliate clubs [[Wellington United]] and [[Lower Hutt City AFC|Lower Hutt City]] in the [[Central League (New Zealand)|Central League]]. On 14 November 2020, Paulsen finally made his reserves debut, starting in a 1–0 loss to [[Team Wellington]] in the opening game of the [[2020–21 New Zealand Football Championship|2020–21]] season. Paulsen remained a consistent starter throughout the season, and despite the team finishing last, Paulsen was named the league's Most Valuable Player.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ellie |date=2021-03-21 |title=Team Wellington crowned 2020/21 ISPS Handa Men's Premiership champions {{!}} ISPS Handa |url=https://ispsgolf.com/team-wellington-crowned-2020-21-isps-handa-mens-premiership-champions/ |access-date=2024-06-19 |language=en-AU}}</ref> His performances for the reserves culminated in his first professional contract, signing for the senior team on a three-year deal alongside fellow reserve standout [[Ben Old]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-sign-academy-players-ben-old-and-alex-paulsen/|title=Wellington Phoenix Sign Academy Players Ben Old and Alex Paulsen|date=13 September 2021}}</ref>

Paulsen entered the [[2021–22 A-League Men]] season as second-choice goalkeeper behind club captain [[Oliver Sail]]. On 19 December 2021, following an injury to Sail, Paulsen made his A-League debut as a substitute in a 2–1 loss against [[Sydney FC]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title='Not up to standard': Wellington Phoenix lose third A-League Men game in a row |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/127326106/not-up-to-standard-wellington-phoenix-lose-third-aleague-men-game-in-a-row |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=19 December 2021 |language=en}}</ref> Paulsen would remain starter in Sail's absence; in an [[2021 FFA Cup|FFA Cup]] quarterfinal match against [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] on 5 January 2022, Paulsen made three saves in a 0–0 (4–3) [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shootout]] [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] win to secure the Phoenix's maiden semifinal appearance in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/127420779/alex-paulsen-saves-the-day-to-send-wellington-phoenix-into-ffa-cup-final-four|title=Alex Paulsen saves the day to send Wellington Phoenix into FFA Cup final four|date=6 January 2022|accessdate=6 January 2022|author=Rollo, Phillip|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref> Upon Sail's return from injury, however, Paulsen returned to a bench role, and he did not make an appearance [[2022–23 A-League Men|the following season]].

====Breakout season====
Sail departed the club to sign with [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]] prior to the start of the [[2023–24 A-League Men|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://perthglory.com.au/news/glory-swoop-to-bring-sail-on-board/|title=Glory swoop to bring Sail on board|date=9 March 2023}}</ref> Paulsen became starting goalkeeper under new head coach [[Giancarlo Italiano]], and played every minute as the Wellington Phoenix finished second, achieving their highest ever finish while conceding the lowest number of goals in club history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2024/04/football-wellington-phoenix-celebrate-record-breaking-a-league-season-amid-weird-wait-for-premiership-fate.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240427194806/https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/sport/2024/04/football-wellington-phoenix-celebrate-record-breaking-a-league-season-amid-weird-wait-for-premiership-fate.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 April 2024|title=Phoenix celebrate recordbreaking A-League season before 'weird' wait for premiership fate|newspaper=[[Newshub]] |via=www.newshub.co.nz}}</ref> Paulsen was named the Wellington Phoenix Members' Player of the Year, Players' Player of the Year and Under–23 Player of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/barry-and-barbarouses-crowned-players-of-the-year/|title=Barry and Barbarouses crowned players of the year|date=30 April 2024}}</ref> He was named [[A-League Men Goalkeeper of the Year]], and shared the [[A-League Men Young Footballer of the Year|Young Footballer of the Year]] award with [[Nestory Irankunda]]; this marked the first ever time a Wellington Phoenix player had won the award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/a-league-award-winners-2023-24-full-list-details/|title=Every Isuzu UTE A-League award winner: Johnny Warren Medalist, Goal of the Year & more|date=25 May 2024}}</ref> He was also named in the [[PFA Footballer of the Year Awards#A-League Men Team of the Season|A-League Men Team of the Season]], receiving the most votes out of any player.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/five-nix-named-to-pfa-team-of-the-season/|title=Five Nix named to PFA team of the season|date=16 May 2024}}</ref> Paulsen's season has since been noted as among the best of any A-League goalkeeper in history.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-06-19 |title=The $4 million man: Why Premier League club chased Kiwi star |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/english-premier-league/premier-league-club-bournemouth-complete-pursuit-of-wellington-phoenix-goalkeeper-alex-paulsen/4RYJUFKV4BBBVDXJ4SMW5NQI7A/ |access-date=2024-06-19 |website=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

On 20 May 2024, Paulsen was called up to the [[A-Leagues All Stars Game|A-League All Stars]] for a friendly match against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]; Paulsen started [[2024 A-Leagues All Stars Men game|the match]] as the All Stars won 8–0.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/five-nix-men-named-to-a-league-all-stars/|title=Five Nix men named to A-League All Stars|date=20 May 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/aleague-all-stars-8-0-newcastle-united-match-report-highlights-video-goals/|title=A-Leagues icon says what everyone is thinking after All Stars demolish Newcastle United|date=24 May 2024}}</ref>

Paulsen left the Phoenix having made 37 first-team appearances, keeping a club-record 11 clean sheets in 27 league matches during the [[2023–24 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2023–24 season]]. He also saved three penalties, denying [[Adam Taggart]], [[Jamie Maclaren]], and [[Ulises Dávila]] from the spot.<ref name="rnz.co.nz">{{Cite web |date=2024-06-05 |title=Wellington Phoenix goalkeeper Alex Paulsen makes landmark move to Premier League |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/news/sport/518676/wellington-phoenix-goalkeeper-alex-paulsen-makes-landmark-move-to-premier-league |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=RNZ |language=en-nz}}</ref> His departure represented a club-record transfer fee, surpassing the previous record set by [[Sarpreet Singh]] to [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bartle |first=Harry |title=Football: Wellington Phoenix goalkeeper Alex Paulsen sold to English Premier League club Bournemouth in record transfer |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/350458155/football-wellington-phoenix-goalkeeper-alex-paulsen-sold-to-english-premier-league-club-bournemouth-in-record-transfer |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=www.stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

===Bournemouth===
In June 2024, Paulsen signed for [[Premier League]] club [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] for a reported initial fee of £850,000, rising to £2 million with add-ons, on a four-year contract running until the end of the 2027–28 season.<ref name="auto1" /><ref name="rnz.co.nz"/>

====Loan to Auckland FC====
Ahead of the [[2024–25 A-League Men]] season, the [[Australian Professional Leagues]], the governing body for the A-League Men, announced the removal of the [[Caceres rule]]; this allowed Paulsen to be loaned to sister club [[Auckland FC]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=jakerosengarten|date=2024-08-08|title='Caceres Clause' to be reviewed ahead of 2024-25 A-Leagues Season|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/a-league-rule-change-caceres-clause-explained-latest-updated/|access-date=2024-08-08|website=A-Leagues|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=jakerosengarten|date=2024-08-08|title=Auckland FC sign Alex Paulsen on loan from AFC Bournemouth: Full details|url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/alex-paulsen-auckland-fc-loan-details-explained-new-zealand-football-all-whites-a-league-transfer-news/|access-date=2024-08-08|website=A-Leagues|language=en-AU}}</ref>

Paulsen was part of an Auckland side that set a new Australian football record by going 532 minutes before conceding their first goal, including a 2–0 win over his former club [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] in the first-ever [[New Zealand Derby (football)|New Zealand Derby]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=By the numbers: Auckland FC break 47-year record with sixth straight victory|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360514558/numbers-auckland-fc-break-47-year-record-sixth-straight-victory#:~:text=532.,minutes%20without%20conceding%20in%201986.|website=www.stuff.co.nz|access-date=2026-01-31|date=December 9, 2024|last=Rollo|first=Phillip}}</ref> Paulsen played every minute as Auckland won the A-League Premiership in their debut season, marking his first major honour at club level. He was named the [[A-League Men Goalkeeper of the Year]] for a second consecutive season and was also included in the [[Professional Footballers Australia]] (PFA) A-League Team of the Season, alongside teammates [[Hiroki Sakai]], [[Francis de Vries]], and [[Louis Verstraete]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=D'Urbano |first=Nicholas |date=2025-05-29 |title=Five Grand Finalists named as PFA announces 2024-25 A-League Men Team of the Season |url=https://pfa.net.au/news/five-grand-finalists-named-as-pfa-announces-2024-25-a-league-men-team-of-the-season/ |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=The PFA |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2025-05-29 |title=Auckland dominate PFA's Team of the Season after historic debut as 5 Grand Finalists named |url=https://aleagues.com.au/news/a-league-men-team-of-the-season-squad-coach-pfa-how-its-picked-full-xi/ |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=A-Leagues |language=en-AU}}</ref>

Paulsen returned to AFC Bournemouth on 12 June 2025, making 28 appearances and keeping 13 clean sheets during his loan spell.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2025-06-12 |title=Alex Paulsen returns to AFC Bournemouth |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/alex-paulsen-returns-to-afc-bournemouth/ |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=Auckland |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Loan to Lechia Gdańsk ====
On 26 August 2025, Bournemouth loaned Paulsen to [[Lechia Gdańsk]] of the Polish [[Ekstraklasa]] for the [[2025–26 Ekstraklasa|2025–26 season]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360802642/afc-bournemouth-send-all-whites-goalkeeper-alex-paulsen-season-long-loan-lechia-gdansk-poland|title=AFC Bournemouth send All Whites goalkeeper Alex Paulsen on season-long loan to Lechia Gdansk in Poland|date=26 August 2025|access-date=26 August 2025|newspaper=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Paulsen loaned to Lechia Gdansk |url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/2025/august/25/paulsen-loaned-to-lechia-gdansk/ |access-date=2026-02-25 |website=www.afcb.co.uk}}</ref>

Paulsen made his first appearance for the club in a 2–0 loss to [[Jagiellonia Białystok]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jagiellonia Białystok vs Lechia Gdańsk: Ekstraklasa stats & head-to-head |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/ckge4pnx4wjt |access-date=2026-02-26 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Two weeks later, he kept his first clean sheet in his second appearance, a 2–0 win over [[GKS Katowice]] on 12 September.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Lechia Gdańsk vs GKS Katowice: Ekstraklasa stats & head-to-head |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c7408r787prt |access-date=2026-02-26 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |title=Lechia Gdańsk Defeats Gks Katowice 2-0 With Goals From Kurminowski and Mena |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/pko-bp-ekstraklasa/articles/lechia-gda-sk-defeats-gks-katowice-2-0-with-goals-from-kurminowski-and-mena-2025-09-12 |access-date=2026-02-26 |website=beIN SPORTS |language=en-us}}</ref>

==International career==
In September 2018, Paulsen was called up for [[New Zealand men's national under-17 football team|New Zealand]] to compete in the [[2018 OFC U-16 Championship]]. Paulsen made three competition appearances, and was presented the Golden Glove award. In the final against the [[Solomon Islands national under-17 football team|Solomon Islands]], Paulsen saved two penalties – one in regular time, one in the penalty shootout – as New Zealand prevailed to win their eighth title, qualifying for the [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in the process.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-09-24 |title=Sport: NZ seal seventh OFC U16 title |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/367135/sport-nz-seal-seventh-ofc-u16-title |access-date=2024-06-19 |website=[[RNZ]] |language=en-nz}}</ref>

Paulsen played in all three of New Zealand's games in the [[2019 FIFA U-17 World Cup]], being eliminated in the group stage. Despite making a high-profile error in a 3–0 loss to [[Brazil national under-17 football team|Brazil]], Paulsen recovered to keep a clean sheet in a 1–0 win over [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/301039178/keeper-calm-and-carrying-on-how-alex-paulsen-bounced-back-from-unfortunate-error | title=Stuff }}</ref>

Aged just 17, Paulsen was called up by [[Des Buckingham]] to the [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand under-23]] squad for the [[2019 OFC Men's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]]. Paulsen made one appearance, as a late substitute in a 6–1 win over [[Samoa national under-23 football team|Samoa]], as New Zealand won the title and qualified for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="oceaniafootball.com">{{cite web | url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/new-zealand-u-23-secure-olympic-qualification/ | title=New Zealand U-23 secure Olympic qualification | date=5 October 2019 }}</ref> [[Danny Hay]] named Paulsen as a traveling reserve for the tournament, with [[Michael Woud]] and [[Jamie Searle]] preferred in the main squad; Paulsen did not make an appearance as New Zealand reached the quarter-finals.<ref name="oceaniafootball.com"/>

In September 2022, Paulsen was first called up to the [[New Zealand men's national football team|senior national team]] for a two-game friendly series against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]], but did not play in either match.<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand Football |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2024-06-19 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref> He was later called up for friendlies against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Ireland]] in November 2023, and then in March 2024 for two [[2024 FIFA Series|FIFA Series]] matches against [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] and [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]], but again did not play ahead of incumbent [[Max Crocombe]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=2023-11-06 |title=Paulsen one of three Nix called up to the All Whites |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/paulsen-one-of-three-nix-called-up-to-the-all-whites/ |access-date=2024-06-19 |website=Wellington Phoenix |language=en-AU}}</ref>

On 18 June 2024, Paulsen finally made his senior international debut, keeping a clean sheet against the [[Solomon Islands national football team|Solomon Islands]] in a 3−0 [[2024 OFC Men's Nations Cup]] win. Crocombe started all subsequent tournament games as New Zealand eventually claimed the trophy.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-mens-nations-cup-2024-group-a-2700242489/new-zealand-solomon-islands-2701555571/ | title=Match }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/all-whites/all-whites-v-vanuatu-live-updates-from-the-oceania-nations-cup-final/SVBR3KJDBZFKJNF2RPBEA6EMVA/ | title=All Whites claim Nations Cup | date=30 June 2024 }}</ref>

Paulsen was recalled to the All Whites for the inaugural New Zealand [[FIFA Series]], featuring matches against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] and [[Chile national football team|Chile]]. He played the full 90 minutes against Chile in a 4–1 victory, which marked New Zealand's first win against a [[CONMEBOL]] opponent and ended their eight-game winless run.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Burgess |first=Michael |date=30 March 2026|title=All Whites get Fifa World Cup boost with emphatic Chile victory |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/all-whites/all-whites-v-chile-live-updates-mens-fifa-series-eden-park/DE7ICBAFDVBATPQE36H6Q6DI7Q/ |access-date=2026-03-30 |website=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |language=en-NZ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Voerman |first=Andrew |title=All Whites break South American duck with morale-boosting win over 10-man Chile |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360952594/all-whites-break-south-american-duck-morale-boosting-win-over-10-man-chile |date=30 March 2026|access-date=2026-03-30 |website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Paulsen attended St Heliers School and [[Selwyn College, Auckland|Selwyn College]] in Auckland, before moving to [[Scots College, Wellington|Scots College]] in Wellington after joining the Wellington Phoenix academy in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SelwynCollegeSport/posts/awesome-alex-attacking-the-wicketsthe-junior-a-boys-cricket-team-wrapped-up-thei/1541135269309088/|title=Facebook|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>

Paulsen's brother, Adam, represents the [[New Zealand national futsal team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sporty.co.nz/aucklandfootball/newsarticle/69411|title=Five Things to Know About AFF Flanker Adam Paulsen}}</ref> The brothers played [[futsal]] regularly growing up, and Paulsen attributes this as a major influence on his ball-playing ability as a goalkeeper.<ref name="auto"/>

